# ---- Poisson Distribution Check ----
if df[date_column_start].notna().sum() > 0:
    df["FireDate"] = df[date_column_start].dt.date
    fire_counts = df.groupby("FireDate").size()

    # Compute Poisson distribution mean ()
    lambda_poisson = np.mean(fire_counts)

    # Generate Poisson probabilities for the observed range
    poisson_dist = poisson.pmf(np.arange(fire_counts.max()), mu=lambda_poisson)

    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
    sns.histplot(fire_counts, bins=30, kde=False, stat="density", label="Observed", color="blue")
    plt.plot(np.arange(fire_counts.max()), poisson_dist, 'r-', label="Poisson Fit")
    plt.xlabel("Number of Fires Per Day")
    plt.ylabel("Probability Density")
    plt.title("Observed vs. Poisson Distribution of Fire Counts")
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

    print(f" Poisson distribution check completed! Mean (): {lambda_poisson:.2f}")
else:
    print(" Skipping Poisson analysis: Missing FireDiscoveryDateTime column.")# ---- Ensure Correct Datetime Columns ----

 Poisson distribution check completed! Mean (): 84.60
In[6]:
# Compute variance and mean
fire_counts_var = np.var(fire_counts)
fire_counts_mean = np.mean(fire_counts)

print(f"Variance: {fire_counts_var:.2f}, Mean: {fire_counts_mean:.2f}")

# If variance > mean, fit a Negative Binomial distribution
if fire_counts_var > fire_counts_mean:
    # Estimate parameters for Negative Binomial
    p = fire_counts_mean / fire_counts_var
    r = (fire_counts_mean ** 2) / (fire_counts_var - fire_counts_mean)

    # Generate Negative Binomial probabilities
    x = np.arange(0, fire_counts.max())
    neg_binom_dist = nbinom.pmf(x, r, p)

    # Plot comparison
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
    sns.histplot(fire_counts, bins=30, kde=False, stat="density", label="Observed", color="blue")
    plt.plot(x, neg_binom_dist, 'r-', label="Negative Binomial Fit")
    plt.xlabel("Number of Fires Per Day")
    plt.ylabel("Probability Density")
    plt.title("Observed vs. Negative Binomial Distribution of Fire Counts")
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

    print(f" Negative Binomial Fit Completed: r = {r:.2f}, p = {p:.2f}")
else:
    print(" Variance is not significantly greater than the mean. Negative Binomial may not be a good fit.")

Variance: 4599.73, Mean: 84.60

 Negative Binomial Fit Completed: r = 1.59, p = 0.02
In[7]:
# Compute fire duration interarrival times
if "FireDuration_Days" in df.columns:
    fire_durations = df["FireDuration_Days"].dropna()  
    
# Fit exponential distribution
    lambda_exp = 1 / np.mean(fire_durations)  #  = 1/mean duration

    # Generate exponential probabilities
    x = np.linspace(0, max(fire_durations), 100)
    exp_pdf = lambda_exp * np.exp(-lambda_exp * x)

    # Plot comparison
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
    sns.histplot(fire_durations, bins=30, kde=False, stat="density", label="Observed", color="blue")
    plt.plot(x, exp_pdf, 'r-', label="Exponential Fit")
    plt.xlabel("Fire Duration (Days)")
    plt.ylabel("Density")
    plt.title("Fire Duration vs. Exponential Distribution")
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

    # Perform Kolmogorov-Smirnov (KS) Test
    ks_stat, ks_p_value = kstest(fire_durations, "expon", args=(0, 1/lambda_exp))

    print(f" Exponential Fit Completed!  = {lambda_exp:.4f}")
    print(f" KS Test: D-statistic = {ks_stat:.4f}, p-value = {ks_p_value:.4f}")

    if ks_p_value > 0.05:
        print(" The data is likely to follow an Exponential distribution (fail to reject H0).")
    else:
        print(" The data does NOT follow an Exponential distribution (reject H0).")
else:
    print(" Skipping Exponential test: FireDuration_Days column is missing.")

 The data does NOT follow an Exponential distribution (reject H0).

# ---- ANOVA: Are Fires Getting Bigger? ----
if "FinalAcres" in df.columns:
    grouped_sizes = [df[df["Year"] == year]["FinalAcres"].dropna() for year in df["Year"].unique()]
    f_stat, p_value = f_oneway(*grouped_sizes)
    print(f"\nANOVA Test: F-statistic = {f_stat:.4f}, p-value = {p_value:.4f}")
    print(" Fires are growing bigger over time!" if p_value < 0.05 else " No significant change in fire sizes.")

# ---- Trend Analysis: Are Wildfires Increasing? ----
if df["FireDate"].notna().sum() > 0:
    fire_counts_sorted = fire_counts.sort_index()
    trend_test = original_test(fire_counts_sorted)
    print(f"\nMann-Kendall Trend Test Result: {trend_test.trend}")
    print(f"p-value: {trend_test.p}, Reject Null? {trend_test.h}")
    print(" Significant increase in wildfires!" if trend_test.h else " No significant trend detected.")

# ---- Do Human-Caused Fires Last Longer? (T-test) ----
if "FireCauseGeneral" in df.columns:
    human_fires = df[df["FireCauseGeneral"] == "Human"]["FireDuration_Days"].dropna()
    natural_fires = df[df["FireCauseGeneral"] == "Natural"]["FireDuration_Days"].dropna()
    
    t_stat, p_val = ttest_ind(human_fires, natural_fires, equal_var=False)
    
    print(f"T-test result: t-statistic={t_stat:.4f}, p-value={p_val:.4f}")
    
    if p_val < 0.05:
        print(" Significant difference: Human-caused fires last longer!")
    else:
        print(" No significant difference in fire duration by cause.")
